      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In ''Diabetes Rises; Doctors Foresee a Harsh Impact'' (front page, Aug. 24), the steep increase in diabetes among Americans is attributed to the increased obesity of our population.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In ''Diabetes Rises; Doctors Foresee a Harsh Impact'' (front page, Aug. 24), the steep increase in diabetes among Americans is attributed to the increased obesity of our population.</p>
        <p>Among the causes of obesity mentioned are time spent in front of televisions and computers, but not mentioned is a far bigger component: cars.</p>
        <p>Our increasingly suburban population creeps from couch to car to office chair; walking is confined to the mall. Children neither walk nor cycle as much as they used to. The heavy traffic in once-quiet suburbia makes cycling dangerous, and the increased distances caused by car-oriented sprawl development make it impractical.</p>
        <p>Occasional bouts of prophylactic or cosmetic ''exercise'' cannot compensate for the absence of physical activity integrated into daily life.</p>
        <p>MICHAEL J. SMITH  New York, Aug. 24, 2000</p>
      </block>
